5|$|John Wood Campbell Jr. (June 8, 1910– July 11, 1971) was an American {{science fiction}} <b>writer</b> <b>and</b> <b>editor.</b> As editor of Astounding Science Fiction (later called Analog Science Fiction and Fact) from late 1937 until his death, he is {{generally}} credited with shaping the Golden Age of Science Fiction.|$|E
5|$|Hillcourt {{worked at}} a BSA camp at Bear Mountain in Harriman State Park, New York, in 1926 where he became an {{instructor}} in American Indian dance. He then worked for the BSA Supply Division where he broke his leg when a crate fell on him. He met James West while working at the national office. West solicited Hillcourt's thoughts on Scouting in the U.S. Hillcourt later sent West an 18-page memo detailing issues {{with the lack of}} patrol structure and leadership. He recommended that the BSA write a handbook for patrol leaders, and that it needed to be written by someone who had been both a patrol leader and a Scoutmaster. West hired Hillcourt as a <b>writer</b> <b>and</b> <b>editor</b> and was later persuaded to commission Hillcourt to write the first Handbook for Patrol Leaders which was published in 1929.|$|E
